# Codex Reviewer Findings — ПССК Prompt Quality Review
Chain: pssk-cv-b2-260416-v12-260416-223329-f82f

## Issues Found
1. [CRITICAL] Fix 3 placement uses an impossible anchor order — The prompt tells the executor to insert `tableIsClosed` “between renderedTableGuestCount and const ordersSum = React.useMemo” and expects `ordersSum` around `~530` after Fix 1. In the actual source, `ordersSum` is at line 490, while Fix 1 inserts after `tableOrdersTotal` at lines 514-523, so `ordersSum` stays above the entire Fix 1 block. Following the prompt literally can trigger unnecessary hook reordering or hesitation about where to place the new memo. PROMPT FIX: In Fix 3 Step 3.2, replace the ordersSum-based placement with a real post-Fix-1 anchor such as “insert immediately after renderedTableGuestCount and before getGuestLabelById”, and remove the incorrect `ordersSum ~530` expectation.

2. [MEDIUM] Fix 2 Step 2.4c rationale contradicts both the replacement code and the frozen bucket order — The note says that when `pending_unconfirmed` exists, `served` “НЕ должен быть collapsed”, but the instructed replacement sets `otherGroupsExist = true`, which collapses `served` by default. The same note also says the user will see `pending_unconfirmed` “first”, while the prompt separately locks `bucketOrder = ['served', 'in_progress', 'pending_unconfirmed']`, so pending remains below served. PROMPT FIX: Rewrite the explanation to say the goal is to prevent `served` auto-expansion when pending exists; pending still renders below served per R1.

3. [MEDIUM] Fix 1’s “rendered-data invariant” is not actually invariant against the rendered table rows — The prompt tells Fix 1 to exclude cancelled orders from `renderedTableTotal`/`renderedTableGuestCount`, but Fix 4 and the AC explicitly keep Section 5 rendering all orders, including cancelled-only guests. That means the header totals can diverge from the visible per-guest cards even though the fix is labeled “rendered-data invariant”. PROMPT FIX: Either filter cancelled orders out of the table/self cards as well, or rename the invariant and explicitly state that header metrics are based on non-cancelled active orders, not all rendered rows.

4. [LOW] Fix 4 contains a stale inline explanation that points back to the weaker cancelled predicate — The injected comment says “Fix 1 filters `o.status !== 'cancelled'` in renderedTableTotal”, but Fix 1/v12 standardizes on `isCancelledOrder(o)` specifically to cover `internal_code === 'cancel'` too. That stale comment can cause a reviewer or executor to “simplify” the code back to raw-status filtering. PROMPT FIX: Change the comment to reference `isCancelledOrder(o)` or delete the parenthetical.

5. [LOW] Regression guidance weakens a now-unambiguous dead-code removal — Fix 1 Step 1.3 correctly removes orphan `submittedTableTotal`, and the current baseline has only one definition and one consumer, but the later Regression Check says “`submittedTableTotal` удалён ... или оставлен если есть другие использования”. That gives reviewers permission to keep dead code even though the prompt already proved the baseline has no surviving uses after Fix 1. PROMPT FIX: Make the v12 regression check unconditional: after Fix 1, `submittedTableTotal` must have 0 hits.

## Summary
Total: 5 issues (1 CRITICAL, 2 MEDIUM, 2 LOW)

## Additional Risks
- The per-table dismissal key `cv_terminal_dismissed_{tableKey}` can suppress the terminal screen across separate dining sessions on the same physical table; the prompt only validates “new tableId”, not “same table reused later”.
- `terminalDismissed` is re-synced in `useEffect`, so a table switch can transiently render with the previous table’s dismissal flag before the effect runs. The prompt does not say whether that one-render flash is acceptable.

## Prompt Clarity (MANDATORY — do NOT skip)
- Overall clarity: 3/5
- What was most clear: scope lock to `CartView.jsx`, the fix order `Fix 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4`, and most grep-based identifier verification are explicit and useful.
- What was ambiguous or could cause hesitation: Fix 3 Step 3.2 uses an impossible placement anchor (`renderedTableGuestCount` before `ordersSum`), and Fix 2 Step 2.4c explains the collapse behavior in two mutually inconsistent ways.
- Missing context: whether cancelled orders should remain visible in the table/self cards if header metrics intentionally exclude them, and whether terminal dismissal is intended to survive a new session on the same table.

## Fix Ratings (MANDATORY — ALWAYS include this section, even if no issues found)
Rate each Fix mentioned in the prompt. Scale: 1=Rewrite needed, 2=Major issues, 3=Needs clarification, 4=Minor issues, 5=Clear.

| Fix | Rating (1-5) | Verdict | Key issue (if any) |
|-----|-------------|---------|-------------------|
| Fix1 | 3/5 | Needs clarification | “Rendered-data invariant” conflicts with later instructions that still render cancelled rows/guests. |
| Fix2 | 3/5 | Needs clarification | Step 2.4c rationale contradicts both the replacement code and the locked bucket order. |
| Fix3 | 2/5 | Rewrite needed | Step 3.2 placement is anchored to an impossible source order (`ordersSum` is above the Fix 1 block). |
| Fix4 | 4/5 | Clear | The fix is mostly actionable, but one inline comment still references the weaker raw-status cancelled check. |

Overall prompt verdict: NEEDS REVISION (any <4/5)
```

